trans-unit.source: Quantize Data
trans-unit.target: Quantize Data

trans-unit.source: Puts numerical data into bins
trans-unit.target: Puts numerical data into bins

trans-unit.source: Category: <link xlink:href="345c5ed4-4dd6-4998-9773-6ca0e00e6946" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Scale and Reduce</link>
trans-unit.target: Category: <link xlink:href="345c5ed4-4dd6-4998-9773-6ca0e00e6946" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Scale and Reduce</link>

trans-unit.source: Module Overview
trans-unit.target: Module Overview

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Quantize Data</ui> module to group or <newTerm>bin</newTerm> numbers, or to flatten the distribution of continuous data.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Quantize Data</ui> module to group or <newTerm>bin</newTerm> numbers, or to flatten the distribution of continuous data.

trans-unit.source: <newTerm>Quantization</newTerm> or <newTerm>binning</newTerm> is useful if you have a column of continuous numbers, with too many values to model, and want to create ranges of values that can be more easily modeled.
trans-unit.target: <newTerm>Quantization</newTerm> or <newTerm>binning</newTerm> is useful if you have a column of continuous numbers, with too many values to model, and want to create ranges of values that can be more easily modeled.

trans-unit.source: Or you might want to replace a column of numbers with categorical values mapped to specific ranges.
trans-unit.target: Or you might want to replace a column of numbers with categorical values mapped to specific ranges.

trans-unit.source: Quantization can be applied only to columns containing all numerical data.
trans-unit.target: Quantization can be applied only to columns containing all numerical data.

trans-unit.source: Each number is mapped to a bin, by comparing its value against the values of the bin edges.
trans-unit.target: Each number is mapped to a bin, by comparing its value against the values of the bin edges.

trans-unit.source: For example, if the value is <math>1.5</math> and the bin edges are <math>1</math>, <math>2</math>, and <math>3</math>, the element would be mapped to bin number 2.
trans-unit.target: For example, if the value is <math>1.5</math> and the bin edges are <math>1</math>, <math>2</math>, and <math>3</math>, the element would be mapped to bin number 2.

trans-unit.source: Value <math>0.5</math> would be mapped to bin number 1 (the underflow bin), and value <math>3.5</math> would be mapped to bin number 4 (the overflow bin)
trans-unit.target: Value <math>0.5</math> would be mapped to bin number 1 (the underflow bin), and value <math>3.5</math> would be mapped to bin number 4 (the overflow bin)

trans-unit.source: <ui>Quantize Data</ui> module supports multiple options for the <ui>Binning mode</ui> parameter.
trans-unit.target: <ui>Quantize Data</ui> module supports multiple options for the <ui>Binning mode</ui> parameter.

trans-unit.source: You can customize how the bin edges are set and how values are apportioned into the bins:
trans-unit.target: You can customize how the bin edges are set and how values are apportioned into the bins:

trans-unit.source: Manually assign bin edges
trans-unit.target: Manually assign bin edges

trans-unit.source: Specify that numbers are binned such that they are distributed evenly.
trans-unit.target: Specify that numbers are binned such that they are distributed evenly.

trans-unit.source: Use entropy scores to calculate the information values for each range and optimize the bins in the predictive model
trans-unit.target: Use entropy scores to calculate the information values for each range and optimize the bins in the predictive model

trans-unit.source: Apportion values such that each bin covers the same interval.
trans-unit.target: Apportion values such that each bin covers the same interval.

trans-unit.source: The values from the data column will be placed in the bins such that each bin has the same interval between starting and end values, even if some bins have more values as a result.
trans-unit.target: The values from the data column will be placed in the bins such that each bin has the same interval between starting and end values, even if some bins have more values as a result.

trans-unit.source: Assign values to bins by using <newTerm>quantiles</newTerm>, or percentile ranks.
trans-unit.target: Assign values to bins by using <newTerm>quantiles</newTerm>, or percentile ranks.

trans-unit.source: Because there are so many approaches, all customizable, we recommend that you experiment with different methods and values.
trans-unit.target: Because there are so many approaches, all customizable, we recommend that you experiment with different methods and values.

trans-unit.source: The <legacyLink xlink:href="#bkmk_Examples" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Examples</legacyLink> section contains links to sample experiments that demonstrate how to use the different binning algorithms.
trans-unit.target: The <legacyLink xlink:href="#bkmk_Examples" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Examples</legacyLink> section contains links to sample experiments that demonstrate how to use the different binning algorithms.

trans-unit.source: How to Configure Quantize Data
trans-unit.target: How to Configure Quantize Data

trans-unit.source: Connect a dataset that has numerical column you want to bin.
trans-unit.target: Connect a dataset that has numerical column you want to bin.

trans-unit.source: Or, use <link xlink:href="1ec722fa-b623-4e26-a44e-a50c6d726223" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Project Columns</link> to select a subset of columns to work with.
trans-unit.target: Or, use <link xlink:href="1ec722fa-b623-4e26-a44e-a50c6d726223" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Project Columns</link> to select a subset of columns to work with.

trans-unit.source: Specify the binning mode, and set related parameters.
trans-unit.target: Specify the binning mode, and set related parameters.

trans-unit.source: See the <legacyLink xlink:href="#bkmk_Options" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Options</legacyLink> section for details.
trans-unit.target: See the <legacyLink xlink:href="#bkmk_Options" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Options</legacyLink> section for details.

trans-unit.source: Each binning method has different parameters so be sure to select the <ui>Binning mode</ui> first.
trans-unit.target: Each binning method has different parameters so be sure to select the <ui>Binning mode</ui> first.

trans-unit.source: Choose the numeric columns to quantize.
trans-unit.target: Choose the numeric columns to quantize.

trans-unit.source: The same binning rule is applied to all applicable columns that you choose.
trans-unit.target: The same binning rule is applied to all applicable columns that you choose.

trans-unit.source: Therefore, if you need to bin some columns by using a different method, use a separate instance of <ui>Quantize Data</ui> for each set of columns.
trans-unit.target: Therefore, if you need to bin some columns by using a different method, use a separate instance of <ui>Quantize Data</ui> for each set of columns.

trans-unit.source: Indicate whether you want the new values to replace the raw data, or to be appended to the original dataset.
trans-unit.target: Indicate whether you want the new values to replace the raw data, or to be appended to the original dataset.

trans-unit.source: You can also choose to output just the new binned values.
trans-unit.target: You can also choose to output just the new binned values.

trans-unit.source: The <ui>Quantize Data</ui> module returns a dataset in which each element has been binned according to the specified mode.
trans-unit.target: The <ui>Quantize Data</ui> module returns a dataset in which each element has been binned according to the specified mode.

trans-unit.source: It also returns a <ui>Binning transformation</ui>, which is a function that can be passed to the <link xlink:href="805e592d-0f1f-48eb-97c9-688ed0c1dc70" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Apply Transformation</link> module to bin new samples of data using the same binning mode and parameters.
trans-unit.target: It also returns a <ui>Binning transformation</ui>, which is a function that can be passed to the <link xlink:href="805e592d-0f1f-48eb-97c9-688ed0c1dc70" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Apply Transformation</link> module to bin new samples of data using the same binning mode and parameters.

trans-unit.source: Options
trans-unit.target: Options

trans-unit.source: <ui>Quantize Data</ui> has the following options:
trans-unit.target: <ui>Quantize Data</ui> has the following options:

trans-unit.source: Binning mode
trans-unit.target: Binning mode

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Entropy MDL</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Entropy MDL</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: The entropy model for binning calculates an information score that indicates how useful a particular bin range might be in the predictive model.
trans-unit.target: The entropy model for binning calculates an information score that indicates how useful a particular bin range might be in the predictive model.

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Quantiles</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Quantiles</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: The quantile method assigns values to bins based on percentile ranks.
trans-unit.target: The quantile method assigns values to bins based on percentile ranks.

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Equal Width</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Equal Width</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: With this option, you must specify the total number of bins.
trans-unit.target: With this option, you must specify the total number of bins.

trans-unit.source: The values from the data column will be placed in the bins such that each bin has the same interval between starting and end values.
trans-unit.target: The values from the data column will be placed in the bins such that each bin has the same interval between starting and end values.

trans-unit.source: As a result, some bins might have more values if data is clumped around a certain point.
trans-unit.target: As a result, some bins might have more values if data is clumped around a certain point.

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Custom Edges</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Custom Edges</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: You can specify the values that begin each bin.
trans-unit.target: You can specify the values that begin each bin.

trans-unit.source: The edge value is always the lower boundary of the bin.
trans-unit.target: The edge value is always the lower boundary of the bin.

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Equal Width with Custom Start and Stop</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Equal Width with Custom Start and Stop</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: This method is like the <ui>Equal Width</ui> option, but you can specify both lower and upper bin boundaries.
trans-unit.target: This method is like the <ui>Equal Width</ui> option, but you can specify both lower and upper bin boundaries.

trans-unit.source: Number of bins
trans-unit.target: Number of bins

trans-unit.source: Type the number of bins, or <newTerm>quantiles</newTerm>, that you want to create.
trans-unit.target: Type the number of bins, or <newTerm>quantiles</newTerm>, that you want to create.

trans-unit.source: This option is available with the Entropy MDL, <ui>Quantiles</ui>, and <ui>Equal Width</ui> binning modes.
trans-unit.target: This option is available with the Entropy MDL, <ui>Quantiles</ui>, and <ui>Equal Width</ui> binning modes.

trans-unit.source: Columns to bin
trans-unit.target: Columns to bin

trans-unit.source: Use the Column Selector to choose the columns that have the values you want to bin.
trans-unit.target: Use the Column Selector to choose the columns that have the values you want to bin.

trans-unit.source: Columns must be a numeric data type.
trans-unit.target: Columns must be a numeric data type.

trans-unit.source: If you choose a column that is not an allowed type, you will not get an error when selecting the columns, only at run time.
trans-unit.target: If you choose a column that is not an allowed type, you will not get an error when selecting the columns, only at run time.

trans-unit.source: Note also that the module returns an error on finding the first column of a disallowed type, so if there multiple columns of an invalid type, the error will not list all invalid columns.
trans-unit.target: Note also that the module returns an error on finding the first column of a disallowed type, so if there multiple columns of an invalid type, the error will not list all invalid columns.

trans-unit.source: Quantile normalization
trans-unit.target: Quantile normalization

trans-unit.source: If you use the <ui>Quantiles</ui> binning mode, you must set this parameter, which determines how values are normalized prior to sorting into quantiles.
trans-unit.target: If you use the <ui>Quantiles</ui> binning mode, you must set this parameter, which determines how values are normalized prior to sorting into quantiles.

trans-unit.source: The options are:
trans-unit.target: The options are:

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Percent</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Percent</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: Values are normalized within the range [1,number of bins]
trans-unit.target: Values are normalized within the range [1,number of bins]

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>PQuantile</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>PQuantile</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: Values are normalized within the range [0,1]
trans-unit.target: Values are normalized within the range [0,1]

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>QuantileIndex</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>QuantileIndex</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: Values are normalized within the range [0,100]
trans-unit.target: Values are normalized within the range [0,100]

trans-unit.source: Comma-separated list of bin edges
trans-unit.target: Comma-separated list of bin edges

trans-unit.source: If you choose the <ui>Custom Edges</ui> option, type a comma-separated list of bin edges.
trans-unit.target: If you choose the <ui>Custom Edges</ui> option, type a comma-separated list of bin edges.

trans-unit.source: The values must be sorted in order that the bins are created, from lowest to highest.
trans-unit.target: The values must be sorted in order that the bins are created, from lowest to highest.

trans-unit.source: First edge position
trans-unit.target: First edge position

trans-unit.source: When you choose the option <ui>Equal Width With Custom Start And Stop</ui>, you must type a value for the lower boundary of the first bin.
trans-unit.target: When you choose the option <ui>Equal Width With Custom Start And Stop</ui>, you must type a value for the lower boundary of the first bin.

trans-unit.source: Last edge position
trans-unit.target: Last edge position

trans-unit.source: When you choose the option <ui>Equal Width With Custom Start And Stop</ui>, you must type a value for the lower boundary of the last bin.
trans-unit.target: When you choose the option <ui>Equal Width With Custom Start And Stop</ui>, you must type a value for the lower boundary of the last bin.

trans-unit.source: Output mode
trans-unit.target: Output mode

trans-unit.source: The output mode specifies how the quantized values are returned:
trans-unit.target: The output mode specifies how the quantized values are returned:

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Append</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Append</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: Creates a new column with the binned values and appends that to the input table.
trans-unit.target: Creates a new column with the binned values and appends that to the input table.

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>Inplace</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>Inplace</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: Replaces the original values with the new values in the dataset.
trans-unit.target: Replaces the original values with the new values in the dataset.

trans-unit.source: <legacyItalic><ui>ResultOnly</ui></legacyItalic>.
trans-unit.target: <legacyItalic><ui>ResultOnly</ui></legacyItalic>.

trans-unit.source: Returns just the result columns.
trans-unit.target: Returns just the result columns.

trans-unit.source: Tag columns as categorical
trans-unit.target: Tag columns as categorical

trans-unit.source: Select this option to automatically add a metadata flag to the column of binned values, which indicates that the quantized columns should be handled as categorical variables.
trans-unit.target: Select this option to automatically add a metadata flag to the column of binned values, which indicates that the quantized columns should be handled as categorical variables.

trans-unit.source: Technical Notes
trans-unit.target: Technical Notes

trans-unit.source: If the column to bin (quantize) is sparse, then the bin index offset (the quantile offset) is used when the resulting column is populated.
trans-unit.target: If the column to bin (quantize) is sparse, then the bin index offset (the quantile offset) is used when the resulting column is populated.

trans-unit.source: The offset is chosen so that sparse 0 always goes to the bin with an index of 0 (in other words, the quantile with value 0).
trans-unit.target: The offset is chosen so that sparse 0 always goes to the bin with an index of 0 (in other words, the quantile with value 0).

trans-unit.source: Sparse zeros are propagated from the input to the output column.
trans-unit.target: Sparse zeros are propagated from the input to the output column.

trans-unit.source: Processing of dense columns always produces results with a minimum bin index equal to 1; that is, the minimum quantile value equals the minimum value in the column.
trans-unit.target: Processing of dense columns always produces results with a minimum bin index equal to 1; that is, the minimum quantile value equals the minimum value in the column.

trans-unit.source: At the same time, processing of a sparse column produces a result with variable minimum bin index (minimum quantile value).
trans-unit.target: At the same time, processing of a sparse column produces a result with variable minimum bin index (minimum quantile value).

trans-unit.source: All NaNs and missing values are propagated from the input column to the output column.
trans-unit.target: All NaNs and missing values are propagated from the input column to the output column.

trans-unit.source: The only exception is the case when the module returns quantile indexes.
trans-unit.target: The only exception is the case when the module returns quantile indexes.

trans-unit.source: In this case all NaNs are promoted to missing values.
trans-unit.target: In this case all NaNs are promoted to missing values.

trans-unit.source: Bin indices are 1-based.
trans-unit.target: Bin indices are 1-based.

trans-unit.source: This is the natural convention for quantiles (1st quantile, 2nd quantile, and so on).
trans-unit.target: This is the natural convention for quantiles (1st quantile, 2nd quantile, and so on).

trans-unit.source: The only exception is the case when the column to bin is sparse.
trans-unit.target: The only exception is the case when the column to bin is sparse.
